{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17488e69-dc42-4ad0-93b0-90447fd23d7d","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's a summary:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed how **test IDs** are computed — they now include the **fully qualified name** (namespace + class + method). Since Azure DevOps tracks history by test ID, every test looks \"new.\"\n\n**Fix:** Add this to your `.csproj` to opt back into the v3 ID scheme while you transition:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it has no associated test method. Accessing `TestName` (or `TestResultsDirectory` etc.) throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it silently returned the first test's name, which was misleading.\n\nYour code on **line 13** hits this:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Guard or remove the access, since class-init runs once before any test:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4;\n    // use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead.\n    var className = context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other key v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | V3 silently coerced mismatched types (e.g., `int` → `long`). V4 is strict — mismatches now fail. |\n| **Test method signatures** | Non-`public` test methods and methods with unexpected return types are now **silently skipped** rather than discovered. |\n| **`[AssemblyInitialize]`/`[AssemblyCleanup]`** | Must now be in a `[TestClass]`-annotated class (enforced at runtime). |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for collections** | V4 compares collections structurally by default; v3 compared references. Tests that relied on reference inequality may flip. |\n| **Parallel execution** | V4 defaults to **method-level** parallelism. If your tests have shared state, add `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable it. |\n| **Timeout behavior** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` cooperatively instead of `Thread.Abort`. Long-running tests may no longer be killed. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to apply the fix for `SetupTests.cs`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"169ed17d-0a13-44f7-b59d-bb0d11bf4d03","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can give a thorough answer about MSTest v4 breaking changes based on my knowledge. Let me address the three concerns:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** — In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation changed. MSTest v3 used a test ID based on the test method name only, while v4 uses a fully qualified name (namespace + class + method). This changes the test ID, so Azure DevOps sees them as new tests with no history.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a \"class-level\" context that doesn't have a specific test name (since it runs before any test). Accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. \n\nIn v3, it would just return the name of the first test method, but v4 removed that behavior.\n\n3. **Other things to watch out for** — There are several other breaking changes worth knowing about in v4.","outputTokens":926,"requestId":"0C03:2A854:B19211:CD762C:69F02388"},"id":"b2158047-c855-4332-af4f-a098b0c0950e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:03:56.798Z","parentId":"6801ab43-a203-4f74-8916-64b0c1a40641"}
